            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Rico Valeriano is a product of two San Franciscos, woven together by family and flavor. Born in Daly City to a Filipino mother who worked as a nurse at SF General and an Italian-American father whose family ran a fish stall at Fisherman's Wharf, Rico\u2019s childhood was a vibrant mix of Tagalog and Italian, adobo and cioppino. He grew up feeling like a bridge between cultures, always observing, always listening.\n\nThis observational nature led him to San Francisco State University, where he dabbled in liberal arts, searching for a narrative that felt like his own. He found it not in a textbook, but in the buzzing creativity of a Haight Street salon where he took a part-time job sweeping floors. He was mesmerized by the artistry, the intimate conversations, and the tangible transformation of a great haircut. He dropped out of college, disappointing his parents, and enrolled in cosmetology school, a decision that felt more honest than any academic paper he\u2019d ever written.\n\nHis career ascended steadily. Rico honed his craft at a high-end salon in Union Square before taking the leap with his colleague and best friend, Lena. Together, they opened *Valeur*, a chic, minimalist salon in Hayes Valley. That was fifteen years ago. A key turning point was navigating the business through the 2008 recession, a trial by fire that solidified their partnership and cemented their place in the neighborhood.\n\nNow at 50, Rico's life is a well-curated routine. He lives in a stylish condo just a 0.8-mile walk from *Valeur*. His mornings begin with an espresso at a local caf\u00e9 where he knows the baristas by name. His days are a blur of consultations with long-term clients\u2014who are more like friends\u2014and managing the business. Single after a long-term relationship ended amicably a few years ago, his social life revolves around a tight-knit circle, dinner parties, and frequenting the SFJAZZ Center.\n\nRico feels deeply connected to Hayes Valley's evolution, watching it grow around him. His dream is no longer about expansion, but about legacy. He aspires to mentor young stylists, passing on his craft. He also quietly saves for a two-month sabbatical to finally explore the small towns of his parents' origins in Italy and the Philippines, hoping to complete the story that began in his childhood kitchen."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was seven, perched on a stool in the Daly City kitchen. His Nonno was loudly explaining the importance of fresh basil for the sauce, while his Lola, with a knowing smirk, insisted a little patis (fish sauce) would make it better. The air was thick with the scent of garlic and the beautiful clash of Italian and Tagalog. In that moment, Rico realized he wasn't divided between two worlds; he *was* the bridge. It taught him to listen, to find harmony in discord, a skill he\u2019d later need.\n\n2.\nHe was 20, a disillusioned SF State student sweeping hair at a noisy Haight Street salon. He stopped, mesmerized, watching a stylist finish a sharp, angled bob. It wasn't just a haircut; it was sculpture. The snip of the shears felt more honest than any lecture, and the client\u2019s joyful gasp in the mirror was a revelation. He understood then that transformation was his craft. Disappointing his parents would hurt, but lying to himself would be worse. He dropped his broom and felt, for the first time, a sense of purpose.\n\n3.\nIt was late 2008. The appointment book was terrifyingly empty. He and Lena sat in the stark silence of *Valeur*, sharing a cheap six-pack under a single lamp. \"We're either going to lose everything or we're going to make this work,\" she\u2019d said, her voice steady. In that shared moment of fear and defiance, something clicked. This wasn't just a business; it was their foxhole. That night cemented a partnership stronger than any contract and taught him that resilience is built in the quiet moments of shared struggle.\n\n4.\nHe remembers the last night with his ex-partner, David, three years ago. There was no shouting, just a shared bottle of wine on their condo\u2019s balcony overlooking the city. \"We're better friends than we are partners now, aren't we?\" David had said, and Rico knew it was true. The sadness was profound but clean\u2014a mature acknowledgment that their story had reached its gentle end. It hurt, but it also taught him the grace of letting go and deepened his appreciation for the quiet contentment of his own company.\n\n5.\nLast autumn, he watched Ana, his newest hire, execute a tricky razor cut he\u2019d spent weeks teaching her. She was nervous but precise, her focus absolute. When the client beamed at the result, Rico felt a surge of pride that was deeper than any personal accomplishment. It wasn't his success anymore; it was hers. In that reflection, he saw his future shift from building a business to building people. His legacy wouldn\u2019t just be the salon, but the hands he helped train to carry on the craft."
